,"1329–Female":"1329–Deceased","1327":"1327","1424":"1424","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","about 1424":"about 1424","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","about 1440":"about 1440","1329":"1329","1516":"1516","Nuneham Courtenay, Oxfordshire, England":"Nuneham Courtenay, Oxfordshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pechy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from a short form of any of various personal names formed with the ancient Germanic element <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. Compare   Brecht   and   Precht  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brecht","meanings":["South German: from a short form of any of various personal names formed with ancient Germanic <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ as the second element, for example   Albrecht  ,   Ruprecht  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":31,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Pechy was born about 1424, in Suffolk, England, her father, Simon de Peche, was 98 and her mother, Agnes Holme, was 96. She had at least 1 son with John Hunt. She died in 1470, at the age of 47."},"et":{"about 1424–1470":"umbes 1424–1470","1424–1470":"1424–1470","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1440–1516":"1440–1516","1327–Male":"1327–Surnud","1329–Female":"1329–Surnud","1327":"1327","1424":"1424","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","about 1424":"umbes 1424","1440":"1440","1470":"1470","about 1440":"umbes 1440","1329":"1329","1516":"1516","Nuneh